{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c2bee306-f5d8-4955-8689-61981e6121d5","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the `cpu-sampling` profile. Here's the workflow:\n\n**1. Install the tool inside the pod:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod> -- bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\nexport PATH=\"$PATH:$HOME/.dotnet/tools\"\n```\n\n**2. Find your process and collect:**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace ps                         # get the PID\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\n**3. Copy the trace out:**\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod>:/path/to/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**4. Analyze** by opening `trace.nettrace` in:\n- **Visual Studio** (Windows) → best UI experience\n- **PerfView** (Windows)\n- **Speedscope** (cross-platform, https://speedscope.app) — convert first:\n  ```bash\n  dotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format Speedscope\n  ```\n\n**Tips:**\n- If the container lacks the .NET SDK, use `dotnet tool install --tool-path /tmp/tools dotnet-trace` instead.\n- For production, prefer `--duration` to avoid unbounded collection.\n- If you also need off-CPU / wait analysis, use `dotnet-trace collect --profile gc-collect` or switch to **`dotnet-counters`** for a quick live view first (`dotnet-counters monitor -p <PID>`).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4cc781c9-03de-4f10-ad52-37eb3a449f60","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a diagnostics/troubleshooting question, not a code change request. I'll provide a concise answer based on my knowledge.","outputTokens":445,"requestId":"640A:14F71D:1572D00:18CA10A:69EC15A7"},"id":"7b15b9be-5637-4dde-ac95-cef40f0f4a48","timestamp":"2026-04-25T01:15:30.154Z","parentId":"fd7eba26-0ae8-44bc-b333-f91d4b9e03ad"}
